('chunk_2dc80f1e9531d4bdc5','file_635d854e419faefdf1','pahe.md','Concept: Dribbling *(focus skill)*','**Definition:** Bouncing the ball on the floor with one hand while moving, to travel legally with the ball (a player may take **up to 3 steps** without dribbling, then must dribble, pass or shoot).

**How to (technique cues):**
1. **Spread fingers** and push the ball down with the fingertips/pad of the hand — do **not** slap with the palm.
2. Keep the bounce **waist height or lower** for control.
3. **Push, don''t slap** — control the ball down and let it come back up.
4. Keep **eyes up** to scan for teammates and defenders, not down at the ball.
5. Dribble with the hand **furthest from the defender**; use the body to shield.

**Real-world / game application:** A winger dribbles into space to draw a defender, then stops and looks up to find an open teammate near the goal.

**Why it matters:** Legal, controlled dribbling lets a player advance and buy time without a travelling violation, and keeps possession under pressure.

**Misconception → Correction:**
- ❌ *"You can run as far as you like as long as you''re holding the ball."*
- ✅ Without dribbling you may take **only up to 3 steps**; you also cannot double-dribble (dribble, hold, then dribble again). Control comes from **fingertips**, not slapping the palm.

**Command-term questions**
1. *(Recall)* **State** how many steps a player may take before dribbling, passing or shooting.
2. *(Apply)* **Demonstrate/Describe** the technique cues for a controlled dribble with the head up.
3. *(Analyse/Evaluate)* **Explain** why keeping "eyes up" while dribbling improves attacking play.','{"concept":1,"dribbling":6,"focus":1,"skill":1,"definition":1,"bouncing":1,"the":18,"ball":6,"floor":1,"with":6,"one":1,"hand":3,"while":2,"moving":1,"travel":1,"legally":1,"player":3,"may":3,"take":3,"steps":3,"without":3,"then":3,"must":1,"dribble":6,"pass":1,"shoot":1,"how":2,"technique":2,"cues":2,"spread":1,"fingers":1,"and":6,"push":2,"down":3,"fingertips":2,"pad":1,"not":3,"slap":2,"palm":2,"keep":2,"bounce":1,"waist":1,"height":1,"lower":1,"for":3,"control":3,"don":1,"let":1,"come":1,"back":1,"eyes":2,"scan":1,"teammates":1,"defenders":1,"furthest":1,"from":2,"defender":2,"use":1,"body":1,"shield":1,"real":1,"world":1,"game":1,"application":1,"winger":1,"dribbles":1,"into":1,"space":1,"draw":1,"stops":1,"looks":1,"find":1,"open":1,"teammate":1,"near":1,"goal":1,"why":2,"matters":1,"legal":1,"controlled":2,"lets":1,"advance":1,"buy":1,"time":1,"travelling":1,"violation":1,"keeps":1,"possession":1,"under":1,"pressure":1,"misconception":1,"correction":1,"you":5,"can":1,"run":1,"far":1,"like":1,"long":1,"holding":1,"only":1,"also":1,"cannot":1,"double":1,"hold":1,"again":1,"comes":1,"slapping":1,"command":1,"term":1,"questions":1,"recall":1,"state":1,"many":1,"before":1,"passing":1,"shooting":1,"apply":1,"demonstrate":1,"describe":1,"head":1,"analyse":1,"evaluate":1,"explain":1,"keeping":1,"improves":1,"attacking":1,"play":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_ef36209495626b68a9','file_635d854e419faefdf1','pahe.md','Concept: Passing *(focus skill)*','**Definition:** Throwing the ball accurately and quickly to a teammate. The most common is the **overarm (shoulder) pass**; short options include the bounce pass and push pass.

**How to (overarm/shoulder pass cues):**
1. Grip the ball with **spread fingers**, ball level with or just above the shoulder.
2. **Step toward the target** with the opposite foot to your throwing arm.
3. Rotate the hips and shoulders, bringing the arm through.
4. **Release with a wrist snap**, following through toward the target.
5. Aim for the receiver''s **chest/hands** so it''s easy to catch.

**Real-world / game application:** Under pressure near the goal area, a quick bounce pass under a defender''s arms reaches a teammate cutting into space to shoot.

**Why it matters:** Passing moves the ball far faster than dribbling, stretches the defence, creates space, and sets up scoring chances. Accurate passing keeps possession.

**Misconception → Correction:**
- ❌ *"The hardest, fastest pass is always the best pass."*
- ✅ The **best pass is the most catchable and appropriate** one. A pass that is too hard or poorly aimed causes turnovers. Choose the pass (bounce, push, overarm) that fits the distance and defenders.

**Command-term questions**
1. *(Recall)* **Identify** which foot steps forward during a right-handed overarm pass.
2. *(Apply)* **Describe** how you would choose between a bounce pass and an overarm pass in a game.
3. *(Analyse/Evaluate)* **Evaluate** why accurate passing is often more valuable than powerful passing. *(Reflection style: reflect on your own passing in the last game — what worked and what to improve?)*

---','{"concept":1,"passing":6,"focus":1,"skill":1,"definition":1,"throwing":2,"the":22,"ball":4,"accurately":1,"and":8,"quickly":1,"teammate":2,"most":2,"common":1,"overarm":5,"shoulder":3,"pass":13,"short":1,"options":1,"include":1,"bounce":4,"push":2,"how":2,"cues":1,"grip":1,"with":4,"spread":1,"fingers":1,"level":1,"just":1,"above":1,"step":1,"toward":2,"target":2,"opposite":1,"foot":2,"your":2,"arm":2,"rotate":1,"hips":1,"shoulders":1,"bringing":1,"through":2,"release":1,"wrist":1,"snap":1,"following":1,"aim":1,"for":1,"receiver":1,"chest":1,"hands":1,"easy":1,"catch":1,"real":1,"world":1,"game":3,"application":1,"under":2,"pressure":1,"near":1,"goal":1,"area":1,"quick":1,"defender":1,"arms":1,"reaches":1,"cutting":1,"into":1,"space":2,"shoot":1,"why":2,"matters":1,"moves":1,"far":1,"faster":1,"than":2,"dribbling":1,"stretches":1,"defence":1,"creates":1,"sets":1,"scoring":1,"chances":1,"accurate":2,"keeps":1,"possession":1,"misconception":1,"correction":1,"hardest":1,"fastest":1,"always":1,"best":2,"catchable":1,"appropriate":1,"one":1,"that":2,"too":1,"hard":1,"poorly":1,"aimed":1,"causes":1,"turnovers":1,"choose":2,"fits":1,"distance":1,"defenders":1,"command":1,"term":1,"questions":1,"recall":1,"identify":1,"which":1,"steps":1,"forward":1,"during":1,"right":1,"handed":1,"apply":1,"describe":1,"you":1,"would":1,"between":1,"analyse":1,"evaluate":2,"often":1,"more":1,"valuable":1,"powerful":1,"reflection":1,"style":1,"reflect":1,"own":1,"last":1,"what":2,"worked":1,"improve":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_77dc2ce33764dfd6a7','file_635d854e419faefdf1','pahe.md','UNIT 3 — Types of Starts (Individual Sports / Athletics)','**Key Concept:** Change
**Related Concepts:** Movement, Energy, Refinement
**Global Context:** Scientific and technical innovation (biomechanics and technique refinement)
**Statement of Inquiry:** *Refining explosive movement lets an athlete convert stored energy into rapid change of speed at the start of a race.*

**Inquiry Questions**
- **Factual:** What are the different types of start and the phases of a block start?
- **Conceptual:** How do fitness components combine to produce a fast, explosive start?
- **Debatable:** Is a fast start more important than finishing strength in a sprint race?

---','{"unit":1,"types":2,"starts":1,"individual":1,"sports":1,"athletics":1,"key":1,"concept":1,"change":2,"related":1,"concepts":1,"movement":2,"energy":2,"refinement":2,"global":1,"context":1,"scientific":1,"and":3,"technical":1,"innovation":1,"biomechanics":1,"technique":1,"statement":1,"inquiry":2,"refining":1,"explosive":2,"lets":1,"athlete":1,"convert":1,"stored":1,"into":1,"rapid":1,"speed":1,"the":3,"start":5,"race":2,"questions":1,"factual":1,"what":1,"are":1,"different":1,"phases":1,"block":1,"conceptual":1,"how":1,"fitness":1,"components":1,"combine":1,"produce":1,"fast":2,"debatable":1,"more":1,"important":1,"than":1,"finishing":1,"strength":1,"sprint":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_f98a9ee4fc8ebe264f','file_635d854e419faefdf1','pahe.md','Concept: Types of Start','| Start type | What it is | Where it''s used |
|-----------|-----------|-----------------|
| **Block Start** | Crouched start using starting blocks for an explosive push-off | Short sprints (100 m, 200 m, hurdles) |
| **Standing Start** | Athlete starts upright from a standing position | Middle- and long-distance runs (800 m+), relay lead-off in some events |
| **Flying Start** | Athlete is already moving/at speed as they cross the start | Relay changeovers, speed training, some timed sprints |
| **Rolling Start** | Begins from a slow roll/jog that builds into full speed | Cycling, motorsport, training drills |
| **Digging Start** | Feet "dig" into the ground/track for grip in a crouched push (without blocks) | Sprinting on surfaces without blocks; sand or informal tracks |

**Why it matters:** The right start suits the event. Explosive block/digging starts win short races where every hundredth of a second counts; standing starts suit longer races where pacing matters more than the initial burst.

**Misconception → Correction:**
- ❌ *"Every race should begin with a crouched block start."*
- ✅ Blocks help **short sprints**. Distance runners use a **standing start** because pacing and energy conservation matter more than an explosive first metre.

**Command-term questions**
1. *(Recall)* **List** five types of start and give an example event for each.
2. *(Apply)* **Select** the most suitable start for (a) a 100 m sprint, (b) an 800 m run, (c) a relay changeover.
3. *(Analyse/Evaluate)* **Compare** a block start and a standing start in terms of speed and energy use.

---','{"100":2,"200":1,"800":2,"concept":1,"types":2,"start":16,"type":1,"what":1,"where":3,"used":1,"block":4,"crouched":3,"using":1,"starting":1,"blocks":4,"for":4,"explosive":3,"push":2,"off":2,"short":3,"sprints":3,"hurdles":1,"standing":5,"athlete":2,"starts":3,"upright":1,"from":2,"position":1,"middle":1,"and":5,"long":1,"distance":2,"runs":1,"relay":3,"lead":1,"some":2,"events":1,"flying":1,"already":1,"moving":1,"speed":4,"they":1,"cross":1,"the":6,"changeovers":1,"training":2,"timed":1,"rolling":1,"begins":1,"slow":1,"roll":1,"jog":1,"that":1,"builds":1,"into":2,"full":1,"cycling":1,"motorsport":1,"drills":1,"digging":2,"feet":1,"dig":1,"ground":1,"track":1,"grip":1,"without":2,"sprinting":1,"surfaces":1,"sand":1,"informal":1,"tracks":1,"why":1,"matters":2,"right":1,"suits":1,"event":2,"win":1,"races":2,"every":2,"hundredth":1,"second":1,"counts":1,"suit":1,"longer":1,"pacing":2,"more":2,"than":2,"initial":1,"burst":1,"misconception":1,"correction":1,"race":1,"should":1,"begin":1,"with":1,"help":1,"runners":1,"use":2,"because":1,"energy":2,"conservation":1,"matter":1,"first":1,"metre":1,"command":1,"term":1,"questions":1,"recall":1,"list":1,"five":1,"give":1,"example":1,"each":1,"apply":1,"select":1,"most":1,"suitable":1,"sprint":1,"run":1,"changeover":1,"analyse":1,"evaluate":1,"compare":1,"terms":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_10584c8f302957d464','file_635d854e419faefdf1','pahe.md','Concept: The Block Start (phase by phase)','**Definition:** A crouched sprint start from starting blocks that maximises the explosive push-off at the gun.

**Phases / cues:**
1. **Set Position:** On "Set", raise the hips slightly **above shoulder height**, weight forward over the hands, back flat, eyes down the track. Body is still and loaded like a spring.
2. **Body Position:** Front knee ~90°, rear knee ~120°, shoulders slightly ahead of the hands, arms straight and shoulder-width behind the line.
3. **Staggered Stance:** Feet on the blocks at different distances — **strong/front foot** closer to the line, rear foot further back — giving powerful, staggered leverage.
4. **Explosive Start:** At the gun, drive **both feet hard against the blocks**, pushing back to move the body forward; arms swing powerfully in opposition to legs.
5. **Drive Phase:** First strides are **low and powerful**, body leaning forward at ~45°, pushing the track behind you to accelerate.
6. **Transition to Upright Sprinting:** Gradually **rise up** over the first ~10–20 m as the body straightens into full sprinting posture.
7. **Finish:** Maintain top speed and technique through the line; lean the chest at the finish.

**Why it matters:** A refined block start converts leg power into forward speed in the crucial first seconds — often the difference between winning and losing a sprint.

**Misconception → Correction:**
- ❌ *"You should stand up straight as fast as possible out of the blocks."*
- ✅ Staying **low with forward lean during the drive phase** produces better acceleration; standing up too early wastes power and slows you. Rise **gradually**.
- ❌ *"Only the front foot pushes off."*
- ✅ **Both feet drive against the blocks** — the rear foot fires first for a quick step, the front foot delivers a longer, powerful push.

**Command-term questions**
1. *(Recall)* **List** the phases of a block start in order.
2. *(Apply)* **Describe** correct hip and body position in the "Set" position.
3. *(Analyse/Evaluate)* **Explain** why staying low in the drive phase improves acceleration. *(Reflection style: after practising, reflect on which phase you found hardest and why.)*

---','{"120":1,"concept":1,"the":30,"block":3,"start":5,"phase":6,"definition":1,"crouched":1,"sprint":2,"from":1,"starting":1,"blocks":5,"that":1,"maximises":1,"explosive":2,"push":2,"off":2,"gun":2,"phases":2,"cues":1,"set":3,"position":4,"raise":1,"hips":1,"slightly":2,"above":1,"shoulder":2,"height":1,"weight":1,"forward":5,"over":2,"hands":2,"back":3,"flat":1,"eyes":1,"down":1,"track":2,"body":6,"still":1,"and":8,"loaded":1,"like":1,"spring":1,"front":4,"knee":2,"rear":3,"shoulders":1,"ahead":1,"arms":2,"straight":2,"width":1,"behind":2,"line":3,"staggered":2,"stance":1,"feet":3,"different":1,"distances":1,"strong":1,"foot":5,"closer":1,"further":1,"giving":1,"powerful":3,"leverage":1,"drive":5,"both":2,"hard":1,"against":2,"pushing":2,"move":1,"swing":1,"powerfully":1,"opposition":1,"legs":1,"first":4,"strides":1,"are":1,"low":3,"leaning":1,"you":4,"accelerate":1,"transition":1,"upright":1,"sprinting":2,"gradually":2,"rise":2,"straightens":1,"into":2,"full":1,"posture":1,"finish":2,"maintain":1,"top":1,"speed":2,"technique":1,"through":1,"lean":2,"chest":1,"why":3,"matters":1,"refined":1,"converts":1,"leg":1,"power":2,"crucial":1,"seconds":1,"often":1,"difference":1,"between":1,"winning":1,"losing":1,"misconception":1,"correction":1,"should":1,"stand":1,"fast":1,"possible":1,"out":1,"staying":2,"with":1,"during":1,"produces":1,"better":1,"acceleration":2,"standing":1,"too":1,"early":1,"wastes":1,"slows":1,"only":1,"pushes":1,"fires":1,"for":1,"quick":1,"step":1,"delivers":1,"longer":1,"command":1,"term":1,"questions":1,"recall":1,"list":1,"order":1,"apply":1,"describe":1,"correct":1,"hip":1,"analyse":1,"evaluate":1,"explain":1,"improves":1,"reflection":1,"style":1,"after":1,"practising":1,"reflect":1,"which":1,"found":1,"hardest":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_61ad78a675ded008f5','file_635d854e419faefdf1','pahe.md','Concept: Fitness Components for Starting','| Component | Definition | Role in the start |
|-----------|-----------|-------------------|
| **Explosive Strength** | Ability to exert maximum force very quickly | Powerful push against the blocks |
| **Speed** | How fast the body/limbs move | Builds velocity through the drive phase |
| **Agility** | Ability to change body position quickly with control | Smooth transition from crouch to sprint |
| **Power** | Strength × speed (force applied fast) | Combines force and quickness at push-off |
| **Flexibility** | Range of motion at joints | Allows a full, effective set position and long stride |
| **Reaction Time** | Time between the stimulus (gun) and the movement | Faster response = quicker off the blocks |
| **Core Stability** | Strength/control of trunk muscles | Keeps the body rigid so leg force transfers into forward motion |

**Why it matters:** No single component wins a start; they **interact**. Great reaction time is wasted without explosive power; power is wasted without core stability to transfer it.

**Real-world application:** A sprinter trains plyometrics (power/explosive strength), reaction drills (reaction time), mobility work (flexibility) and core exercises (core stability) — together they shave time off the start.

**Misconception → Correction:**
- ❌ *"A fast start is just about how strong your legs are."*
- ✅ A start needs **several fitness components working together** — reaction time, power, core stability and flexibility all matter, not leg strength alone.

**Command-term questions**
1. *(Recall)* **Define** "power" and "reaction time".
2. *(Apply)* **Suggest** one training exercise to improve each of two components used in the start.
3. *(Analyse/Evaluate)* **Evaluate** which fitness component you think matters most for a fast start, and justify your choice.

---','{"concept":1,"fitness":3,"components":3,"for":2,"starting":1,"component":3,"definition":1,"role":1,"the":10,"start":7,"explosive":3,"strength":5,"ability":2,"exert":1,"maximum":1,"force":4,"very":1,"quickly":2,"powerful":1,"push":2,"against":1,"blocks":2,"speed":2,"how":2,"fast":4,"body":3,"limbs":1,"move":1,"builds":1,"velocity":1,"through":1,"drive":1,"phase":1,"agility":1,"change":1,"position":2,"with":1,"control":2,"smooth":1,"transition":1,"from":1,"crouch":1,"sprint":1,"power":6,"applied":1,"combines":1,"and":7,"quickness":1,"off":3,"flexibility":3,"range":1,"motion":2,"joints":1,"allows":1,"full":1,"effective":1,"set":1,"long":1,"stride":1,"reaction":6,"time":7,"between":1,"stimulus":1,"gun":1,"movement":1,"faster":1,"response":1,"quicker":1,"core":5,"stability":4,"trunk":1,"muscles":1,"keeps":1,"rigid":1,"leg":2,"transfers":1,"into":1,"forward":1,"why":1,"matters":2,"single":1,"wins":1,"they":2,"interact":1,"great":1,"wasted":2,"without":2,"transfer":1,"real":1,"world":1,"application":1,"sprinter":1,"trains":1,"plyometrics":1,"drills":1,"mobility":1,"work":1,"exercises":1,"together":2,"shave":1,"misconception":1,"correction":1,"just":1,"about":1,"strong":1,"your":2,"legs":1,"are":1,"needs":1,"several":1,"working":1,"all":1,"matter":1,"not":1,"alone":1,"command":1,"term":1,"questions":1,"recall":1,"define":1,"apply":1,"suggest":1,"one":1,"training":1,"exercise":1,"improve":1,"each":1,"two":1,"used":1,"analyse":1,"evaluate":2,"which":1,"you":1,"think":1,"most":1,"justify":1,"choice":1}'::jsonb),
