('chunk_d782a7b6314f91124e','file_635d854e419faefdf1','pahe.md','Concept: The Eight Limbs (Ashtanga)','**Definition:** Patanjali''s Eight Limbs are the eight parts of a complete yoga practice — a path for living, not only postures.

| # | Limb (as in syllabus) | Meaning |
|---|-----------------------|---------|
| 1 | **Ethical Principles — Yamas** | Moral restraints toward others (non-violence, truthfulness, non-stealing) |
| 2 | **Ethical Principles — Niyamas** | Personal observances (cleanliness, contentment, self-discipline) |
| 3 | **Physical Postures (Asana)** | The physical poses that build strength, balance and flexibility |
| 4 | **Breath Control (Pranayama)** | Controlling and extending the breath to steady body and mind |
| 5 | **Meditation and Mindfulness (Dhyana)** | Sustained focus and meditative awareness |
| 6 | **Philosophical Inquiry (Jnana Yoga)** | The path of knowledge and self-understanding |
| 7 | **Devotion and Surrender (Bhakti Yoga)** | The path of love, devotion and letting go |
| 8 | **Selfless Service (Karma Yoga)** | The path of selfless action and service to others |

> Note: The classical Eight Limbs also include *Pratyahara* (withdrawal of senses), *Dharana* (concentration) and *Samadhi* (absorption). The syllabus above groups the limbs together with the three yogic *paths* (Jnana, Bhakti, Karma) to show the breadth of yoga.

**Why it matters:** Yoga develops the whole person — how we treat others (Yamas), ourselves (Niyamas), our body (Asana), our breath (Pranayama) and our mind (Dhyana). Asana, the physical limb, is just one of eight.

**Misconception → Correction:**
- ❌ *"Yoga is only about the poses (asana)."*
- ✅ Poses are **one of eight limbs**. Yoga also includes ethics, breath control, meditation and paths of knowledge, devotion and service.

**Command-term questions**
1. *(Recall)* **List** four of the Eight Limbs of yoga.
2. *(Apply)* **Give an example** of how a student could practise a Yama or Niyama at school.
3. *(Analyse/Evaluate)* **Explain** why asana is only one part of a full yoga practice.

---','{"concept":1,"the":16,"eight":7,"limbs":6,"ashtanga":1,"definition":1,"patanjali":1,"are":2,"parts":1,"complete":1,"yoga":10,"practice":2,"path":4,"for":1,"living":1,"not":1,"only":3,"postures":2,"limb":2,"syllabus":2,"meaning":1,"ethical":2,"principles":2,"yamas":2,"moral":1,"restraints":1,"toward":1,"others":3,"non":2,"violence":1,"truthfulness":1,"stealing":1,"niyamas":2,"personal":1,"observances":1,"cleanliness":1,"contentment":1,"self":2,"discipline":1,"physical":3,"asana":5,"poses":3,"that":1,"build":1,"strength":1,"balance":1,"and":13,"flexibility":1,"breath":4,"control":2,"pranayama":2,"controlling":1,"extending":1,"steady":1,"body":2,"mind":2,"meditation":2,"mindfulness":1,"dhyana":2,"sustained":1,"focus":1,"meditative":1,"awareness":1,"philosophical":1,"inquiry":1,"jnana":2,"knowledge":2,"understanding":1,"devotion":3,"surrender":1,"bhakti":2,"love":1,"letting":1,"selfless":2,"service":3,"karma":2,"action":1,"note":1,"classical":1,"also":2,"include":1,"pratyahara":1,"withdrawal":1,"senses":1,"dharana":1,"concentration":1,"samadhi":1,"absorption":1,"above":1,"groups":1,"together":1,"with":1,"three":1,"yogic":1,"paths":2,"show":1,"breadth":1,"why":2,"matters":1,"develops":1,"whole":1,"person":1,"how":2,"treat":1,"ourselves":1,"our":3,"just":1,"one":3,"misconception":1,"correction":1,"about":1,"includes":1,"ethics":1,"command":1,"term":1,"questions":1,"recall":1,"list":1,"four":1,"apply":1,"give":1,"example":1,"student":1,"could":1,"practise":1,"yama":1,"niyama":1,"school":1,"analyse":1,"evaluate":1,"explain":1,"part":1,"full":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_aa8f86a3b80d3aab29','file_635d854e419faefdf1','pahe.md','4.4 Sitting Yoga Asanas','> **General cautions for all sitting asanas:** work within a pain-free range; never force the knees or back; use a folded blanket/cushion under the hips if the back rounds; avoid deep leg-folding poses if you have a recent knee, hip or ankle injury; breathe smoothly throughout.','{"sitting":2,"yoga":1,"asanas":2,"general":1,"cautions":1,"for":1,"all":1,"work":1,"within":1,"pain":1,"free":1,"range":1,"never":1,"force":1,"the":3,"knees":1,"back":2,"use":1,"folded":1,"blanket":1,"cushion":1,"under":1,"hips":1,"rounds":1,"avoid":1,"deep":1,"leg":1,"folding":1,"poses":1,"you":1,"have":1,"recent":1,"knee":1,"hip":1,"ankle":1,"injury":1,"breathe":1,"smoothly":1,"throughout":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_9b58918fd755db4a29','file_635d854e419faefdf1','pahe.md','Concept: Sukhasana (Easy Pose)','**How to get into it:**
1. Sit on the floor (or a folded blanket) with legs crossed.
2. Cross the shins comfortably, each foot resting under the opposite knee.
3. Lengthen the spine tall, relax the shoulders down.
4. Rest the hands on the knees; breathe slowly.

**Benefits:** Calms the mind, improves posture, opens the hips, good base for breathing and meditation.
**Cautions:** If the knees are higher than the hips or the back rounds, **sit up on a cushion**. Ease off with knee discomfort. Change the leg cross regularly.

**Misconception → Correction:**
- ❌ *"Sukhasana looks easy, so it doesn''t do anything."*
- ✅ Despite the name "Easy Pose", it actively trains **upright posture, hip mobility and calm breathing** — foundational skills for all seated practice.

**Command-term questions**
1. *(Recall)* **State** two benefits of Sukhasana.
2. *(Apply)* **Describe** how to set up Sukhasana correctly for a student with tight hips.
3. *(Analyse/Evaluate)* **Explain** why good spinal alignment matters in seated poses.','{"concept":1,"sukhasana":4,"easy":3,"pose":2,"how":2,"get":1,"into":1,"sit":2,"the":14,"floor":1,"folded":1,"blanket":1,"with":3,"legs":1,"crossed":1,"cross":2,"shins":1,"comfortably":1,"each":1,"foot":1,"resting":1,"under":1,"opposite":1,"knee":2,"lengthen":1,"spine":1,"tall":1,"relax":1,"shoulders":1,"down":1,"rest":1,"hands":1,"knees":2,"breathe":1,"slowly":1,"benefits":2,"calms":1,"mind":1,"improves":1,"posture":2,"opens":1,"hips":3,"good":2,"base":1,"for":3,"breathing":2,"and":2,"meditation":1,"cautions":1,"are":1,"higher":1,"than":1,"back":1,"rounds":1,"cushion":1,"ease":1,"off":1,"discomfort":1,"change":1,"leg":1,"regularly":1,"misconception":1,"correction":1,"looks":1,"doesn":1,"anything":1,"despite":1,"name":1,"actively":1,"trains":1,"upright":1,"hip":1,"mobility":1,"calm":1,"foundational":1,"skills":1,"all":1,"seated":2,"practice":1,"command":1,"term":1,"questions":1,"recall":1,"state":1,"two":1,"apply":1,"describe":1,"set":1,"correctly":1,"student":1,"tight":1,"analyse":1,"evaluate":1,"explain":1,"why":1,"spinal":1,"alignment":1,"matters":1,"poses":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_670bf10051a6cdf3aa','file_635d854e419faefdf1','pahe.md','Concept: Padmasana (Lotus Pose)','**How to get into it:**
1. Sit tall with legs extended.
2. Bend the **right** knee and place the **right foot on the left thigh**, sole facing up.
3. Bend the **left** knee and place the **left foot on the right thigh**, sole facing up.
4. Keep the spine long, knees moving gently toward the floor; hands rest on the knees.

**Benefits:** Deepens hip flexibility, promotes stillness and steady posture for meditation, calms the mind.
**Cautions:** An **advanced pose** — do **not** force the knees. Never enter Padmasana with a knee, ankle or hip injury. Warm up the hips first; if there is any knee pain, use **Ardha Padmasana or Sukhasana** instead.

**Misconception → Correction:**
- ❌ *"Everyone should be able to sit in full lotus quickly."*
- ✅ Padmasana requires significant **open hips** and is often reached over months/years. Forcing it risks **knee injury**. Progress via half lotus and easy pose.

**Command-term questions**
1. *(Recall)* **Identify** where each foot is placed in Padmasana.
2. *(Apply)* **Suggest** a safer alternative for a student who cannot yet do full lotus.
3. *(Analyse/Evaluate)* **Evaluate** why forcing the knees into lotus is unsafe.','{"concept":1,"padmasana":5,"lotus":5,"pose":3,"how":1,"get":1,"into":2,"sit":2,"tall":1,"with":2,"legs":1,"extended":1,"bend":2,"the":13,"right":3,"knee":5,"and":5,"place":2,"foot":3,"left":3,"thigh":2,"sole":2,"facing":2,"keep":1,"spine":1,"long":1,"knees":4,"moving":1,"gently":1,"toward":1,"floor":1,"hands":1,"rest":1,"benefits":1,"deepens":1,"hip":2,"flexibility":1,"promotes":1,"stillness":1,"steady":1,"posture":1,"for":2,"meditation":1,"calms":1,"mind":1,"cautions":1,"advanced":1,"not":1,"force":1,"never":1,"enter":1,"ankle":1,"injury":2,"warm":1,"hips":2,"first":1,"there":1,"any":1,"pain":1,"use":1,"ardha":1,"sukhasana":1,"instead":1,"misconception":1,"correction":1,"everyone":1,"should":1,"able":1,"full":2,"quickly":1,"requires":1,"significant":1,"open":1,"often":1,"reached":1,"over":1,"months":1,"years":1,"forcing":2,"risks":1,"progress":1,"via":1,"half":1,"easy":1,"command":1,"term":1,"questions":1,"recall":1,"identify":1,"where":1,"each":1,"placed":1,"apply":1,"suggest":1,"safer":1,"alternative":1,"student":1,"who":1,"cannot":1,"yet":1,"analyse":1,"evaluate":2,"why":1,"unsafe":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_6c46a2f4b427bf3dd2','file_635d854e419faefdf1','pahe.md','Concept: Ardha Padmasana (Half Lotus Pose)','**How to get into it:**
1. Sit tall with legs extended.
2. Bend one knee and place that **foot on the opposite thigh**, sole up.
3. Tuck the **other foot under the opposite thigh/shin** (as in easy pose), rather than up on the thigh.
4. Lengthen the spine; hands on knees; breathe evenly. Swap sides in another session.

**Benefits:** A **midway step between Sukhasana and Padmasana** — opens the hips, improves posture and steadiness with less strain on the knees than full lotus.
**Cautions:** Keep the lifted knee comfortable; if it lifts high or hurts, support it or return to Sukhasana. Alternate which leg is on top to stay balanced.

**Misconception → Correction:**
- ❌ *"Half lotus is pointless — you should just do full lotus."*
- ✅ Ardha Padmasana is an important **progression pose**: it safely builds the hip flexibility needed for full lotus while being gentler on the knees.

**Command-term questions**
1. *(Recall)* **State** how Ardha Padmasana differs from full Padmasana.
2. *(Apply)* **Describe** how half lotus can be used to progress toward full lotus safely.
3. *(Analyse/Evaluate)* **Explain** why alternating the top leg is important in seated cross-legged poses.

