('chunk_d75cc10c6185ffccfb','file_8378b145fc1fad06fd','physics.md','Unit 1: Measurements and Motion','- **Key Concept:** Relationships
- **Related Concepts:** Movement, Patterns, Evidence
- **Global Context:** Scientific and technical innovation — how measurement and models let us describe and predict motion.
- **Statement of Inquiry:** Accurate measurement reveals patterns in movement that allow us to describe and predict how objects change position over time.
- **Inquiry Questions:**
  - **Factual:** What is the difference between distance and displacement, and between speed and velocity?
  - **Conceptual:** How does the slope of a graph reveal the relationship between two measured quantities?
  - **Debatable:** Is any measurement ever truly "accurate," or only accurate enough for its purpose?','{"unit":1,"measurements":1,"and":8,"motion":2,"key":1,"concept":1,"relationships":1,"related":1,"concepts":1,"movement":2,"patterns":2,"evidence":1,"global":1,"context":1,"scientific":1,"technical":1,"innovation":1,"how":3,"measurement":3,"models":1,"let":1,"describe":2,"predict":2,"statement":1,"inquiry":2,"accurate":3,"reveals":1,"that":1,"allow":1,"objects":1,"change":1,"position":1,"over":1,"time":1,"questions":1,"factual":1,"what":1,"the":3,"difference":1,"between":3,"distance":1,"displacement":1,"speed":1,"velocity":1,"conceptual":1,"does":1,"slope":1,"graph":1,"reveal":1,"relationship":1,"two":1,"measured":1,"quantities":1,"debatable":1,"any":1,"ever":1,"truly":1,"only":1,"enough":1,"for":1,"its":1,"purpose":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_641525a8f143a5f286','file_8378b145fc1fad06fd','physics.md','Fundamental vs Derived Quantities','**Definition.** A *fundamental (base) quantity* cannot be defined in terms of other quantities; it is measured directly and forms the foundation of the SI system. A *derived quantity* is built by combining fundamental quantities through multiplication or division.

**Real-world example.** Length (fundamental) is measured directly with a ruler; speed (derived) is length divided by time.

**Analogy.** Fundamental quantities are like the primary colours; derived quantities are the shades you mix from them.

**Why it matters.** Every equation in physics is dimensionally consistent because derived units trace back to base units — this lets you check whether a formula is even possible.

| Type | Quantity | SI Unit | Symbol |
|------|----------|---------|--------|
| Fundamental | Length | metre | m |
| Fundamental | Mass | kilogram | kg |
| Fundamental | Time | second | s |
| Fundamental | Temperature | kelvin | K |
| Fundamental | Electric current | ampere | A |
| Derived | Area | square metre | m² |
| Derived | Volume | cubic metre | m³ |
| Derived | Speed / velocity | metre per second | m/s |
| Derived | Density | kilogram per cubic metre | kg/m³ |
| Derived | Acceleration | metre per second squared | m/s² |

**Misconception.** *"Weight is a fundamental quantity like mass."* Believed because both are measured in daily life. Wrong because weight is a force (derived: mass × acceleration, newtons); mass is the fundamental quantity in kilograms. Corrective: mass is base, weight is derived from mass and gravity.

**Command-term questions.**
1. *State* two fundamental quantities and their SI units. (recall)
2. *Show* that the unit of density can be written in terms of fundamental units only. (apply)
3. *Explain* why speed is classified as a derived quantity rather than a fundamental one. (analyse)','{"fundamental":15,"derived":13,"quantities":6,"definition":1,"base":3,"quantity":6,"cannot":1,"defined":1,"terms":2,"other":1,"measured":3,"directly":2,"and":3,"forms":1,"the":6,"foundation":1,"system":1,"built":1,"combining":1,"through":1,"multiplication":1,"division":1,"real":1,"world":1,"example":1,"length":3,"with":1,"ruler":1,"speed":3,"divided":1,"time":2,"analogy":1,"are":3,"like":2,"primary":1,"colours":1,"shades":1,"you":2,"mix":1,"from":2,"them":1,"why":2,"matters":1,"every":1,"equation":1,"physics":1,"dimensionally":1,"consistent":1,"because":3,"units":4,"trace":1,"back":1,"this":1,"lets":1,"check":1,"whether":1,"formula":1,"even":1,"possible":1,"type":1,"unit":2,"symbol":1,"metre":6,"mass":6,"kilogram":2,"second":3,"temperature":1,"kelvin":1,"electric":1,"current":1,"ampere":1,"area":1,"square":1,"volume":1,"cubic":2,"velocity":1,"per":3,"density":2,"acceleration":2,"squared":1,"misconception":1,"weight":3,"believed":1,"both":1,"daily":1,"life":1,"wrong":1,"force":1,"newtons":1,"kilograms":1,"corrective":1,"gravity":1,"command":1,"term":1,"questions":1,"state":1,"two":1,"their":1,"recall":1,"show":1,"that":1,"can":1,"written":1,"only":1,"apply":1,"explain":1,"classified":1,"rather":1,"than":1,"one":1,"analyse":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_b65c9a3824ef883b29','file_8378b145fc1fad06fd','physics.md','Unit Conversions','**Definition.** Converting a measurement from one unit to another of the same quantity by multiplying by a conversion factor equal to 1.

**Real-world example.** A road sign gives 90 km/h; to use it in a physics formula you convert to 25 m/s.

**Analogy.** Like exchanging currency — the amount of "value" stays the same, only the label changes.

**Why it matters.** Mixing units (cm with m, minutes with seconds) is the most common source of wrong answers in numerical work.

**Worked example.** Convert 72 km/h to m/s.
72 km/h × (1000 m / 1 km) × (1 h / 3600 s) = 72 × 1000 / 3600 = **20 m/s**.
(Shortcut: divide km/h by 3.6.)

**Misconception.** *"To convert km/h to m/s you multiply by 1000."* Wrong because you must also convert hours to seconds. Corrective: divide by 3.6 (i.e. ×1000 ÷ 3600).

**Command-term questions.**
1. *Convert* 5 km into metres. (recall)
2. *Calculate* the speed 36 km/h in m/s. (apply)
3. *Explain* why a conversion factor must equal one for the physical quantity to stay unchanged. (analyse)','{"1000":4,"3600":3,"unit":2,"conversions":1,"definition":1,"converting":1,"measurement":1,"from":1,"one":2,"another":1,"the":7,"same":2,"quantity":2,"multiplying":1,"conversion":2,"factor":2,"equal":2,"real":1,"world":1,"example":2,"road":1,"sign":1,"gives":1,"use":1,"physics":1,"formula":1,"you":3,"convert":5,"analogy":1,"like":1,"exchanging":1,"currency":1,"amount":1,"value":1,"stays":1,"only":1,"label":1,"changes":1,"why":2,"matters":1,"mixing":1,"units":1,"with":2,"minutes":1,"seconds":2,"most":1,"common":1,"source":1,"wrong":2,"answers":1,"numerical":1,"work":1,"worked":1,"shortcut":1,"divide":2,"misconception":1,"multiply":1,"because":1,"must":2,"also":1,"hours":1,"corrective":1,"command":1,"term":1,"questions":1,"into":1,"metres":1,"recall":1,"calculate":1,"speed":1,"apply":1,"explain":1,"for":1,"physical":1,"stay":1,"unchanged":1,"analyse":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_75ce2edb6015e19853','file_8378b145fc1fad06fd','physics.md','Precision and Accuracy','**Definition.** *Accuracy* is how close a measurement is to the true value. *Precision* is how close repeated measurements are to each other (their spread), independent of the true value.

**Real-world example.** A bathroom scale that always reads 2 kg high is precise (consistent) but not accurate.

**Analogy.** A dartboard: accurate = darts near the bullseye; precise = darts clustered tightly, even if off-centre.

**Why it matters.** Good science needs both — data that are precise but inaccurate hide a systematic fault.

**Described diagram.** Picture four dartboards: (1) scattered and off-centre = neither; (2) tight cluster off-centre = precise not accurate; (3) spread around centre = accurate not precise; (4) tight cluster on centre = both.

**Misconception.** *"Precise and accurate mean the same thing."* Believed because both sound like "good measurement." Wrong because a stuck instrument can be perfectly repeatable yet always wrong. Corrective: precision = agreement of repeats; accuracy = closeness to truth.

**Command-term questions.**
1. *Define* accuracy and precision. (recall)
2. *Identify* whether a scale reading consistently 0.5 kg too high is a precision or accuracy problem. (apply)
3. *Evaluate* a data set with a small spread but a large offset from the accepted value. (evaluate)','{"precision":5,"and":4,"accuracy":5,"definition":1,"how":2,"close":2,"measurement":2,"the":5,"true":2,"value":3,"repeated":1,"measurements":1,"are":2,"each":1,"other":1,"their":1,"spread":3,"independent":1,"real":1,"world":1,"example":1,"bathroom":1,"scale":2,"that":2,"always":2,"reads":1,"high":2,"precise":6,"consistent":1,"but":3,"not":3,"accurate":5,"analogy":1,"dartboard":1,"darts":2,"near":1,"bullseye":1,"clustered":1,"tightly":1,"even":1,"off":3,"centre":5,"why":1,"matters":1,"good":2,"science":1,"needs":1,"both":3,"data":2,"inaccurate":1,"hide":1,"systematic":1,"fault":1,"described":1,"diagram":1,"picture":1,"four":1,"dartboards":1,"scattered":1,"neither":1,"tight":2,"cluster":2,"around":1,"misconception":1,"mean":1,"same":1,"thing":1,"believed":1,"because":2,"sound":1,"like":1,"wrong":2,"stuck":1,"instrument":1,"can":1,"perfectly":1,"repeatable":1,"yet":1,"corrective":1,"agreement":1,"repeats":1,"closeness":1,"truth":1,"command":1,"term":1,"questions":1,"define":1,"recall":1,"identify":1,"whether":1,"reading":1,"consistently":1,"too":1,"problem":1,"apply":1,"evaluate":2,"set":1,"with":1,"small":1,"large":1,"offset":1,"from":1,"accepted":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_ad467225a2a69f1dcd','file_8378b145fc1fad06fd','physics.md','The Scientific Method','**Definition.** A systematic process for investigating questions: observe → ask a question → form a hypothesis → design and perform an experiment → collect and analyse data → draw a conclusion → communicate and repeat.

**Real-world example.** Testing whether a heavier ball rolls down a ramp faster: predict, time several trials, average, conclude.

**Analogy.** A recipe you refine each time you cook — each attempt improves the next.

**Why it matters.** It makes findings testable, repeatable, and open to challenge — the heart of MYP Criteria B and C.

**Misconception.** *"A hypothesis is just a guess."* Wrong because a hypothesis is a *testable, reasoned* prediction, usually in an "if… then…" form. Corrective: it must be falsifiable by an experiment.

**Command-term questions.**
1. *List* the main steps of the scientific method in order. (recall)
2. *Formulate* a testable hypothesis for the ramp experiment. (apply)
3. *Explain* why repeating trials strengthens a conclusion. (analyse)','{"the":6,"scientific":2,"method":2,"definition":1,"systematic":1,"process":1,"for":2,"investigating":1,"questions":2,"observe":1,"ask":1,"question":1,"form":2,"hypothesis":4,"design":1,"and":5,"perform":1,"experiment":3,"collect":1,"analyse":2,"data":1,"draw":1,"conclusion":2,"communicate":1,"repeat":1,"real":1,"world":1,"example":1,"testing":1,"whether":1,"heavier":1,"ball":1,"rolls":1,"down":1,"ramp":2,"faster":1,"predict":1,"time":2,"several":1,"trials":2,"average":1,"conclude":1,"analogy":1,"recipe":1,"you":2,"refine":1,"each":2,"cook":1,"attempt":1,"improves":1,"next":1,"why":2,"matters":1,"makes":1,"findings":1,"testable":3,"repeatable":1,"open":1,"challenge":1,"heart":1,"myp":1,"criteria":1,"misconception":1,"just":1,"guess":1,"wrong":1,"because":1,"reasoned":1,"prediction":1,"usually":1,"then":1,"corrective":1,"must":1,"falsifiable":1,"command":1,"term":1,"list":1,"main":1,"steps":1,"order":1,"recall":1,"formulate":1,"apply":1,"explain":1,"repeating":1,"strengthens":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_a6638dbfcbb6ef98ae','file_8378b145fc1fad06fd','physics.md','Area and Volume (Regular and Irregular Objects)','**Definition.** *Area* is the amount of surface a shape covers (m²). *Volume* is the amount of space a 3-D object occupies (m³).

**Real-world example.** A rectangular tank''s volume tells you how much water it holds; an oddly shaped stone''s volume is found by displacement.

**Analogy.** Volume by displacement is like measuring your body by how much bathwater overflows when you get in.

**Why it matters.** Volume is needed for density, and density identifies materials and predicts floating/sinking.

**Method for regular objects.** Measure dimensions and apply formulas — rectangular block V = length × width × height; cylinder V = πr²h.

**Method for irregular objects (displacement).** Fill a measuring cylinder to a known volume, lower the object in, read the new volume; the rise equals the object''s volume. For a stone: 50 mL → 68 mL means volume = 18 mL = 18 cm³.

**Misconception.** *"Bigger objects always have more volume than smaller ones."* Wrong because shape matters — a flat sheet can spread wide yet hold little volume. Corrective: volume depends on all three dimensions, not overall appearance.

**Command-term questions.**
1. *State* the SI unit of volume. (recall)
2. *Calculate* the volume of a block 4 cm × 3 cm × 2 cm. (apply)
3. *Describe and justify* how you would find the volume of an irregular key using displacement, and why the method works. (analyse)','{"area":2,"and":7,"volume":16,"regular":2,"irregular":3,"objects":4,"definition":1,"the":10,"amount":2,"surface":1,"shape":2,"covers":1,"space":1,"object":3,"occupies":1,"real":1,"world":1,"example":1,"rectangular":2,"tank":1,"tells":1,"you":3,"how":3,"much":2,"water":1,"holds":1,"oddly":1,"shaped":1,"stone":2,"found":1,"displacement":4,"analogy":1,"like":1,"measuring":2,"your":1,"body":1,"bathwater":1,"overflows":1,"when":1,"get":1,"why":2,"matters":2,"needed":1,"for":4,"density":2,"identifies":1,"materials":1,"predicts":1,"floating":1,"sinking":1,"method":3,"measure":1,"dimensions":2,"apply":2,"formulas":1,"block":2,"length":1,"width":1,"height":1,"cylinder":2,"fill":1,"known":1,"lower":1,"read":1,"new":1,"rise":1,"equals":1,"means":1,"misconception":1,"bigger":1,"always":1,"have":1,"more":1,"than":1,"smaller":1,"ones":1,"wrong":1,"because":1,"flat":1,"sheet":1,"can":1,"spread":1,"wide":1,"yet":1,"hold":1,"little":1,"corrective":1,"depends":1,"all":1,"three":1,"not":1,"overall":1,"appearance":1,"command":1,"term":1,"questions":1,"state":1,"unit":1,"recall":1,"calculate":1,"describe":1,"justify":1,"would":1,"find":1,"key":1,"using":1,"works":1,"analyse":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_fd161dc868ac1d1518','file_8378b145fc1fad06fd','physics.md','Density (Solids)','**Definition.** Density is mass per unit volume: how much matter is packed into a given space. Formula: **density = mass ÷ volume** (ρ = m / V), unit kg/m³ or g/cm³.

**Real-world example.** A small lead fishing weight feels heavy for its size because lead is very dense; a large foam block feels light.

**Analogy.** A crowded lift (high density) versus a nearly empty one (low density) of the same size.

**Why it matters.** Density predicts whether something floats, and helps identify unknown materials.

**Described diagram.** A bar chart of densities: cork (~0.24), water (1.0), aluminium (2.7), iron (7.9), gold (19.3) g/cm³ — the taller the bar, the more mass squeezed into each cm³.

**Worked example.** A metal cube has mass 240 g and volume 30 cm³.
Density = mass ÷ volume = 240 ÷ 30 = **8 g/cm³** (likely iron/steel).

**Misconception.** *"Heavier objects are always denser."* Wrong because a huge low-density object can outweigh a tiny dense one. Corrective: density compares mass *for the same volume*, not total mass.

**Command-term questions.**
1. *State* the formula for density and its unit. (recall)
2. *Calculate* the density of a 50 g object with volume 25 cm³. (apply)
3. *Explain* why a steel ship floats even though steel is denser than water. (analyse)','{"240":2,"density":11,"solids":1,"definition":1,"mass":7,"per":1,"unit":3,"volume":6,"how":1,"much":1,"matter":1,"packed":1,"into":2,"given":1,"space":1,"formula":2,"real":1,"world":1,"example":2,"small":1,"lead":2,"fishing":1,"weight":1,"feels":2,"heavy":1,"for":3,"its":2,"size":2,"because":2,"very":1,"dense":2,"large":1,"foam":1,"block":1,"light":1,"analogy":1,"crowded":1,"lift":1,"high":1,"versus":1,"nearly":1,"empty":1,"one":2,"low":2,"the":7,"same":2,"why":2,"matters":1,"predicts":1,"whether":1,"something":1,"floats":2,"and":3,"helps":1,"identify":1,"unknown":1,"materials":1,"described":1,"diagram":1,"bar":2,"chart":1,"densities":1,"cork":1,"water":2,"aluminium":1,"iron":2,"gold":1,"taller":1,"more":1,"squeezed":1,"each":1,"worked":1,"metal":1,"cube":1,"has":1,"likely":1,"steel":3,"misconception":1,"heavier":1,"objects":1,"are":1,"always":1,"denser":2,"wrong":1,"huge":1,"object":2,"can":1,"outweigh":1,"tiny":1,"corrective":1,"compares":1,"not":1,"total":1,"command":1,"term":1,"questions":1,"state":1,"recall":1,"calculate":1,"with":1,"apply":1,"explain":1,"ship":1,"even":1,"though":1,"than":1,"analyse":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_0335c6049aa4978cef','file_8378b145fc1fad06fd','physics.md','Least Count','**Definition.** The least count of an instrument is the smallest value it can measure — the size of one smallest division on its scale.

**Real-world example.** A metre ruler marked in mm has a least count of 1 mm (0.1 cm); a stopwatch reading to 0.01 s has a least count of 0.01 s.

**Analogy.** Like the smallest coin in a currency — you cannot measure change finer than it.

**Why it matters.** The least count sets the limit of a measurement''s precision and its uncertainty.

**Misconception.** *"You can read a ruler to any number of decimal places."* Wrong because you cannot report finer than half the least count. Corrective: precision is capped by the instrument''s least count.

**Command-term questions.**
1. *State* the least count of a millimetre ruler. (recall)
2. *Determine* the least count of a stopwatch that displays 00:00.00. (apply)
3. *Explain* how a smaller least count improves a measurement. (analyse)','{"least":10,"count":10,"definition":1,"the":10,"instrument":2,"smallest":3,"value":1,"can":2,"measure":2,"size":1,"one":1,"division":1,"its":2,"scale":1,"real":1,"world":1,"example":1,"metre":1,"ruler":3,"marked":1,"has":2,"stopwatch":2,"reading":1,"analogy":1,"like":1,"coin":1,"currency":1,"you":3,"cannot":2,"change":1,"finer":2,"than":2,"why":1,"matters":1,"sets":1,"limit":1,"measurement":2,"precision":2,"and":1,"uncertainty":1,"misconception":1,"read":1,"any":1,"number":1,"decimal":1,"places":1,"wrong":1,"because":1,"report":1,"half":1,"corrective":1,"capped":1,"command":1,"term":1,"questions":1,"state":1,"millimetre":1,"recall":1,"determine":1,"that":1,"displays":1,"apply":1,"explain":1,"how":1,"smaller":1,"improves":1,"analyse":1}'::jsonb);